 Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Lancaster in northwestern England, which is recorded as <i>Loncastre</i> in 1086. The place takes its name from the river Lune + Old English <i>ceaster</i> ‘city, Roman fortification’ (from Latin <i>castra</i> ‘legionary camp’). The river name is probably British, perhaps related to Gaelic <i>slán</i> ‘healthy’, ‘salubrious’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir William De Lancaster was born in 1335, in Rydal, Westmorland, England, United Kingdom, his father, John De Lancaster, was 70 and his mother, Lady Annora Moulton, was 68. He married Lady Aline de Gernat in 1360, in Rydal, Westmorland, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died on 14 October 1361, in Westmorland, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 26."},"et":{"1335–6 Oct 1361":"1335–14. oktoober 1361","1289–Male":"1289–Surnud","1293–Female":"1293–Surnud","1335–1361":"1335–1361","1335–1375":"1335–1375","1360–1433":"1360–1433","1265–1334":"1265–1334","1267–1338":"1267–1338","1361":"1361","1360":"1360","1293":"1293","1338":"1338","Abt 1360":"umbes 1360","1335":"1335","1334":"1334","1433":"1433","1267":"1267","1289":"1289","1265":"1